# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Pygame visualization
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Layout
# ──────
#   The window is split into two regions stacked vertically:
#     • Board area  : n×TILE pixels with GAP-pixel gutters between cells.
#     • Info bar    : INFO_H pixels tall - displays "Move k / total" or "Solved!".
#
#   TILE is computed from a target board pixel width so the window scales
#   cleanly for n=3, 4, or 5 without manual adjustment.
#
# Animation model
# ───────────────
#   After A* completes, the solution path is a list of states.  We replay
#   them by "popping" one state at a time from the front of the list.  For
#   each consecutive pair (state_a, state_b):
#     1. find_move()  - identifies which tile moved and its from/to indices.
#     2. draw_frame() - renders state_a with that tile sliding toward its
#                       destination, at fractional progress ∈ [0, 1].
#     3. After ANIM_FRAMES animation frames, snap to state_b and hold for
#        HOLD_FRAMES before beginning the next move.
#
#   Position interpolation uses a smoothstep curve  t = p²(3-2p)  so the
#   tile eases in and out rather than moving at constant velocity.
#
# Tile colors
# ───────────
#   Each tile value is mapped to an HSV color: hue cycles from blue-violet
#   (h≈0.62) through the spectrum over the full tile range.  Saturation and
#   value are fixed for a vibrant-but-readable look.  A drop shadow and a
#   thin top-edge highlight give each tile a subtle 3-D appearance.



# ── State machine ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# phase:  "intro"     -- showing initial board, waiting ~1 s then auto-start
#         "animating" -- sliding a tile between states
#         "holding"   -- tile has landed, brief pause before next move
#         "solved"    -- all moves complete
#
# step  = index into path of the state currently on-screen
# frame = frames elapsed in the current phase